1 oz. evoo.

1 tbl. garlic, chopped
1 tbl. ginger, chopped 
2 oz.gochujang, Korean chili paste
2 tsp. honey
28 oz. tomatoes, if can use San Marzano

Method: in a medium size pot lightly sweat the first 4 ingredients until tender, approx, 15 on low heat. Add remaining ingredients and cook on medium heat for 30 minutes. Remove from heat and blend smooth. Adjust heat levels and sweetness with either more Korean chili paste and honey.

insta_description:
Today's #WorldwideWednesday Comes from San Francisco California. The legendary Gold Coast of Pacific Heights is an elite enclave on Outer Broadway known for its majestic homes, notable residents and unsurpassed views. Here, on a coveted corner lot set high above the city and the bay, this imposing 11,600Â± sq.ft. mansion is the foremost offering on the market in San Francisco, presenting a rare opportunity to own a custom-built residence in a world-class location with world-class views. Impressively engineered of concrete and steel and completed circa 2004, it displays quality construction, craftsmanship and refinement. â â €
â â €
The eminently comfortable home has six bedroomsâ€”five en suiteâ€”seven full baths, and two half baths. Floors are clad in walnut, raw limestone and marble. High-ceilinged public spaces are airy, open, and ideal for entertaining on any scale. The centerpiece of the home is a spectacular serpentine staircase with ornate railings crafted by Italian artisans. The property features interior design by both Ken Fulk and Eric Cohler, elevator access to four levels, a secondary back staircase, smart home technology, radiant heating, two working fireplaces, hand-plastered walls, mahogany doors and windows, a four-car garage with an EV charging station, and abundant storage. Unparalleled, panoramic views unfold from the Golden Gate Bridge and the Marin Headlands, across San Francisco Bay, and all the way to the Oakland Hills, showcasing such landmarks as the Palace of Fine Arts, Alcatraz and Angel Island. â â €
â â €
Also known as Billionaire's Row, these three tranquil blocks offer respite from busy city life yet are just blocks from the boutiques, restaurants and shops of fashionable Sacramento Street. Nearby are Julius Kahn Playground as well as the Presidio - a national park and historic district - which offers the Presidio Golf Course, miles of trails, picnic areas, museums, restaurants, Crissy Field, and Baker Beach.â â €
â â €

Year-over-year growth continues
-
Sales in #2020 have outpaced those of #2019 across all recreational marijuana markets. This is a fundamental characteristic of a growing industry.
-
But the degree to which sales over the previous weekend â€“ and also on Monday â€“ outperformed sales during the same time period in 2019 fell well outside the norm.
-
On average, year-over-year adult-use sales on Fridays between Jan. 10Â and March 6Â were up 70% in California, 9% in Colorado and 8% in Washington state.
-
The average year-over-year increase for adult-use sales on Mondays between Jan. 6Â and March 9Â was 71% in California, 10% in Colorado and 15% in Washington state â€“ meaning the percent increases seen in each market on Monday, March 16, 2020, were several standard deviations beyond the norm.
-
In each market, the sales figures posted on Monday looked much more like a typical Friday, which is usually the biggest sales day of the week for retail cannabis stores.

In these unprecedented times of instability and stock market chaos the first thing that gets cut is discretionary spending. Yes, I mean art. It is also a perfect time to re-evaluate my vision and create something new. During uncertain times we look for security and safety. As as artist I can create the world that I desire within my work. As I scan back in history one time that sticks out as carefree and exciting was the 1950â€™s California Surf culture. Between the cool cars, the rebellious attitudes, and the surf music it gives a sense of calm that we need right now. I am thinking of doing some smaller works on paper with this theme. Leave a comment if interested?

insta_description:
(Reuters) - Millions of California's Bay area residents can still legally light up as cannabis facilities are exempt from a #cornonavirus lockdown that has shuttered most businesses in #SanFrancisco and nearby cities.
-
Cannabis store managers say they have lines longer than local grocery shops and waiting room only. Most staff at a dozen stores reached Tuesday evening said they were too busy to talk to Reuters.
-
"Oh man, we're flooded. As soon as people heard we were still open, they started lining up," said Anthony Barajas, the general manager of Cana Culture in #SanJose.
-
"Once all the toilet paper got sold out, they knew they needed some relief," he said.
-
#Bars, #clubs, #gyms and other businesses all closed Monday under one of the strictest orders made so far in the United States aimed at stemming the coronavirus #pandemic. Around 7 million people reside in the area affected by the orders.
-
Cannabis stores and vendors join the short list of "essential" places that can stay open along with grocery stores, pharmacies and doctors offices, the San Jose Mercury News and other media reported, citing the state's Bureau of Cannabis Control and local officials.
-
#California has more than 500 confirmed cases of coronavirus and at least 12 people have died.
-

insta_description:
So important right now.

Mental health care simply doesn't have the funding that it needs and many vulnerable groups(minorities, the #lgbtq community, and those in poverty) don't have access to good mental health care or treatment at all. This can be devastatingâ€”as proper treatment of severe mental illness can be the difference between life and death.

During times of crisis like what we are going through right now, I am actually encouraged by what I am seeing in terms of mental health professionals doing to make care accessible through alternative methods like #telemedicine, but we need to be diligent in ensuring that everyone at risk within the mental health community can receive help if they need it right now.

insta_description:
I hope you are all doing well during these crazy times.  Social media says business owners have to post every day to stay relevant.  Its hard during times like this to find the motivation, and it feels a little strange to try and post about photography and tips etc when you're going through a pandemic. But the show must go on, 
Pro Tip: Make sure your wedding photographer and other professionals are insured, many are facing the tough decision of cancelling their weddings or pushing the date back which is so sad, but an ensured team will be ideal in situations like these. Always ask your wedding professionals if they are insured or their policy for rescheduling before booking. 
Also please check on your small business owner friends, because this is really a hard time, filled with uncertainty about where or when our next gigs or customers will come from. We cannot rely on our employers to give us PTO because we are our employers.  Also shout out to all the medical, safety, human services workers, hospitality and grocery store workers who are still working diligently to provide quality care for all of us in quarantine, and teachers who are still putting together lesson plans and virtual classrooms while their students are driving their parents crazy at home. You all are the real MVP's. It'll get better you guys.

Before, it used to be about Milah being skeptical around people, but as she got used to people, I just got accustomed to being wanted to be left alone when Iâ€™m walking at night. Herbal formulas.
These formulas are in pill form so no stinky, hard to drink decoctions. (anyone who was forced to drink these as a kid knows what I'm talking about!)
I have a good supply, but am limited by my source, who is being inundated by extra orders. It's been shown that certain TCM formulas were used in China, in conjunction with Western medicine to help alleviate symptoms (such as weakness, cough and lunch function). These are not a cure for  COVID19 or even the flu. But rather a way to support immunity and any symptoms you may have. 
Have other issues? Chronic back pain? Stress and anxiety? Headaches? Menstrual pains? 
I've got herbs for that too! These are a great complement to acupuncture treatments, but can be used as a great stand alone therapy!
I'm doing herbal consultations by phone or email. Please email me at sophia@embrace-acu.com to schedule a consult. We can figure out payment over the phone and herb drop off/pick up if you are local. 
Got any other questions regarding acupuncture and its benefits? I'm conducting free (up to 15 mins) phone consultations! Email me to schedule something!

Stay safe and healthy!

insta_description:
Una leggenda sulla creazione dei brownies Ã¨ quella di Bertha Palmer, una mondana di Chicago, il cui marito possedeva il Palmer House Hotel. Un giorno nel 1893, chiese ad un pasticcere di creare un dolce adatto alle donne che frequentavano il Chicago World's Columbian Exposition. Chiese poi che il dolce fosse simile ad un piccolo pezzo di torta e che si potesse consumare anche durante un pranzo al sacco. 
Il risultato fu chiamato Palmer House Brownie, che conteneva noci ed era ricoperto di glassa alle albicocche.

Tutt'oggi al Palmer House Hotel viene servito un dolce ai clienti che si dice venga fatto usando la stessa ricetta originale.
Il nome fu dato poco dopo il 1893, ma non venne usato da libri di cucina o riviste dell'epoca.

Una torta al cioccolato tagliata a pezzetti che arrecano tanto piacere e un color marrone da fare invidia!

I may ride my bicycle or run or hike.  Even a walk would help break up the monotony of being stuck in the house for 3 weeks.  And without a daily commute or 8 hours a day of clients, Iâ€™ve got plenty of time on my hands.

insta_description:
This is what I love â€” the esoteric, outside the box, â€œdidnâ€™t know it existedâ€ type of stuff. Enter @lolawines Malvasia Bianca, St. Helena, Napa Valley 2018. Vinified from a 4-acre parcel of 45-year-old vines in northern St. Helena, Winemaker Seth Cripe has created one of the most delicious small production white wines in the ValleyğŸ·

While achieving ripeness can be somewhat of an easy feat here in the Valley, the Malvasia is vertically trained to manage vigor and large clusters. Come harvest time, grapes are picked at low PH and around 22 brix, in an effort to produce a lean crisp white wine that represents the purity of the vineyard and varietalğŸ·

Once the grapes are brought in, 70% are whole cluster pressed with that juice undergoing a native cool fermentation to dryness in neutral oak barrels. The other 30% is fermented on the skins and pulp, in an effort to add complexity and texture on the palate. The wine is racked once at bottling and has minimal S02 additions of under 35ppm total from harvest to bottling. Bottling is both unfined and unfilteredğŸ·

The end result is a vibrant and fresh white wine with intense aromatics of passionfruit, nectarine, peach, and apricot. The palate is weighty and textural, but carries with it a backbone of acidity that carries the wine through on the finish. It is truly a delightful and delicious fermented beverage. 124 cases produced. BTG at @pressnapavalleyğŸ·
.

insta_description:
Since I've been a child, I have looked ahead; some call it "having my head in the clouds", but I've come to learn forward thinking gives me hope, motivation, and helps get me through some of the more unpleasant parts of life.

I'm going to start a new series titled "Where We Will Go", focusing on places that I (and hopefully you too) would like to visit once everything has settled and it is advised to travel for leisure again.

I'll be uploading photos from my favorite destinations and inviting people in the local hospitality, entertainment, food service, and tourism industry industry in these locations to share with us what makes them special and to tell my followers why we all should come visit them when we can.

So many of us are affected by what is currently going on in the world, especially local businesses relying on the tourism industry. And if we can't physically be with them now, we can start planning how we can be with them in the near future. But I can't do it without you!

If you have any friends/family/ colleagues that would like to be featured, let me know; hotels, cafes, bakeries, tour guides, restaurants, you name it! I want to showcase them all. I've tagged a few businesses and friends that I currently have stock photos for, but please feel free to send more my way!  My first destination will be the #SanDiego #California area.

Let's look ahead to grand adventures together.

#wherewewillgo #travel #tourism #supportlocal #travelphotography #travelgram #keepmovingforward #lookahead #positivity #sandiego #lajolla #pacificbeach #oceanbeach

With everything going on right now Iâ€™ve been trying to keep my son busy by doing a different activity with him every day. Today we made play dough from scratch. It was so easy and I canâ€™t lie, even I had fun with it ğŸ˜œ stay safe everyone ğŸ™ğŸ¼ and just think of this as more time to bond with your loved ones â¤ï¸ğŸ§¡ğŸ’šğŸ’™ (INGREDIENTS) 
1 cup flour
2 tsp cream of tartar
1/2 cup salt
1 tbsp cooking oil Olive oil or vegetable oil
1 cup water
food coloring 
In a large bowl, combine all of your dry ingredients (flour, salt, cream of tartar) and mix well. -Mix food coloring with your water first. Then add the vegetable oil and water with food coloring to a large pot. Mix together. -Add the dry ingredients to your pot and mix well. -Cook over low to medium heat until the dough starts to form and becomes dry -Once it starts to form a ball together and looks fully cooked, take off the heat. Let the dough cool first before touching. -
Once cool, knead the dough for 5 minutes to make the dough soft.

Now that youâ€™re done making your playdough, get out some cookie cutters and have fun making shapes! We also like using rolling pins and stamps to play with our playdough.

Finding the light. ğŸŒ
Today I shed my first tears for whatâ€™s happening in the world. The mix of emotions went something like this:
* Sadness for my friends and family losing work as shops close, festivals are cancelled, music tours come to a halt, travel restrictions are implemented, bars and restaurants empty out, yoga studios close, hairdressers hang up their scissors, etc etc.
* Hope as I see so many magical people figuring out ways to bring a little light into our homes right now.
* Anger as I see others ignoring whatâ€™s happened in Italy and in Paris, and now in San Francisco, Seattle, NYC and New Orleans for example. Iâ€™m disgusted that people continue to go on as if they donâ€™t have to participate collectively in flattening the curve.
* Relief after talking to the guy servicing my car â€” when I told him I was practicing quarantine and wouldnâ€™t be coming in to get it he said â€œbaby (in a way only New Orleanians can say â€œbabyâ€), donâ€™t you worry about something like a car, you take care of you and yours right now.â€ My head literally fell to the table when I hung up from that call.

_
And in all of that, I feel lucky. I can work from home, my partner is here with me. We have food and shelter and a warm bed and sunshine and each other. I am often called an â€œeternal optimistâ€ â€” I live to create high vibes and hold space for others. And I suppose I share this, because truly, weâ€™re all going to cycle through these emotions. Weâ€™re all going to experience this differently, but the more we can meet this shadow the world is facing collectively head on, the better. ğŸŒ—
_
Itâ€™s not lost on me that the Spring equinox is upon us. Spring is a time of rebirth and awakenings as the Earth rises from the cold into new life. Letâ€™s all practice rising, waking up, and facing the light in a new way. Love you all! xx ~ Andi // ğŸ“·: @elle.hendrix #mystication #joshuatree

How are you doing under quarantine? Better question, what are you doing?! Fortunately I already worked from home so my routine hasnâ€™t changed much. However I have been trying to stay home more than usual, I hadnâ€™t left the house since Saturday until today as I had important errands to run. -

Anyways, Iâ€™m always wondering what my next meal will be, quarantine or not. Anyone that knows me knows that I hate to waste a meal on something I didnâ€™t enjoy. So as Iâ€™m limiting my visits to the store, I was starting to be disappointed at thinking my dinner would be another soup, lentils or pasta. (Although pasta is my favorite!) Fortunately I had some frozen oysters from @lidlbulgaria and immediately fried oyster tacos came to mind!!
-

I know, I just posted a tacos recipe but this one is different yet just as delicious. After making my tortillas, I ran my frozen oysters under lukewarm water for 1 minute and then dried them off. Then I dipped them in whisked eggs, rolled them in flour and pan fried them once the pan was hot. -

To roast the chickpeas and get them crunchy (Iâ€™m obsessed with chickpeas lately) , you must blot them with a paper towel before drizzling olive oil on them. Blotting the extra liquid helps them get the crisp, otherwise theyâ€™ll just steam in the oven. -

Once the oysters and chickpeas are ready, assemble with whatever you like! I chose red cabbage for color, avocado, yogurt and hot sauce! After tonightâ€™s tacos, my husband named me the tortilla master ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ he needs to go to Mexico! Or even just California ğŸ˜‰ -
